'''Aldwark''' is a village and [[civil parish]] in the [[Hambleton]] district of [[North Yorkshire]], [[England]].  It has a population of 116 (2001 census), and is situated on the [[River Ouse, Yorkshire|River Ouse]] about 14 miles from [[York]]. The village lies within a conservation area.

==History==

The name derives from the Old Saxon, ''ald weorc'', meaning ''Old Fort'' and probably refers to the Roman fort guarding the ferry crossing on the old Roman road to [[York]] that passed through here.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tollerton.net/index.php/aldwark|title=Etymology|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref><ref name="Bulmers">{{cite book|title=Bulmer's Topography, History and Directory (Private and Commercial) of North Yorkshire 1890 |page=640|year=1890 |publisher= S&N Publishing|isbn= 1-86150-299-0|accessdate=2010-11-19}}</ref> The village is mentioned in the ''[[Domesday Book]]'' as ''Adewera'' and belonged to Ligulf in the Bulford Hundred. It was handed over to [[Robert, Count of Mortain|Count Robert of Mortain]] by 1086.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://domesdaymap.co.uk/place/SE4663/aldwark/|title=Domesday Book Entry|accessdate= 20 October 2012}}</ref>

==Governance==

The village lies within the [[Thirsk and Malton (UK Parliament constituency)|Thirsk and Malton Parliamentary constituency]]. It also lies within the Easingwold electoral division of North Yorkshire County Council and the Tollerton ward of Hambleton District Council.

The parish council has been combined with those of [[Flawith]] and [[Youlton]] to form Aldwark Area Parish. There are six councillors, three of which represent Aldwark.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tollerton.net/index.php/parish-council-aldwark|title= Combined parish council|accessdate= 20 October 2012}}</ref>

==Demography==

According to the 2001 census, the population was 116 in 50 households. Of these, 31 are detached dwellings and 18 of them are owner occupied. Of the total population, 102 are over 16 years old and 69 are in employment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadDatasetList.do?a=7&b=797653&c=aldwark&d=16&g=475740&i=1001x1003&m=0&r=1&s=1350769318774&enc=1&domainId=15|title=Demographics|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref>

==Geography==

The village is located on the east bank of the [[River Ure]] of about 2,236 acres in size. The soil is primarily [[sand]].<ref name="Bulmers">{{cite book|title=Bulmer's Topography, History and Directory (Private and Commercial) of North Yorkshire 1890 |page=640|year=1890 |publisher= S&N Publishing|isbn= 1-86150-299-0|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref> There is a toll bridge over the river leading to [[Great Ouseburn]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tollerton.net/index.php/history-of-aldwark|title=Toll Bridge|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref>

It has a two areas of woodland called Aldwark Wood and Aldwark Bridge Wood to the south of the village.

There is a river monitoring station at Aldwark Bridge. River levels normally range between {{convert|0.02|m}} and {{convert|3.00|m}}, with the record high level being {{convert|5.17|m}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/riverlevels/120701.aspx?stationId=8004|title=River Level Monitoring|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref>

==Village amenities==

The village is the location for the Aldwark Manor Golf Club & Spa Hotel and Rising Sun Fisheries. There is a public house, the ''Aldwark Arms'', in the village.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aldwarkarms.co.uk/contactus.html|title=Public House|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref> The village is serviced by one bus route between [[Easingwold]] and York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stephensonsofeasingwold.co.uk/images/uploads/orange-zone-timetable-20101209.pdf|title=Bus route|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref>

==Religion==

The church, dedicated to St Stephen, is a quirky design by the Victorian architect [[Edward Buckton Lamb]].<ref name=nyorks>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RoBmT9G9y5gC&pg=PA58&dq|title=Yorkshire: The North Riding|series=The Buildings of England|first=Nikolaus|last= Pevsner|
publisher=Yale University Press|year=1981|isbn=9780300096651}}</ref> It is a Grade II listed building that was consecrated in 1854.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tollerton.net/index.php/st-stephen-church|title=Church|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref>

